						<div style='float:right;margin:0px 0px 15px 15px;font-size:12px;color:#aaa'>2016-02-18 8:26 am</div>
				                <div>Hello Randhir,<br />
<br />
If you're having problems with SEO due to your re-directs, then you need to consolidate the web pages and reduce the number of re-directs.  It's confusing and the search engines are unable to make sense of it - leading to the issues with your rankings.  You can always remove your re-directs as they're in your .htaccess file.   You will simply have to decide how to re-organize the content.  If you have OLD links that lead to the content, then you need to create re-directs that lead to the content, but you should keep them as minimal as possible.   You should also close your old content after a period of time if your new site is already indexed in the search engine,  then no one should be going to your old site/page.  If they're still going to the old page - that will also affect your search engine rankings.  Remove the old page - make sure that everyone is going to your new content.  Check out <a href="https://searchenginewatch.com/sew/how-to/2288690/how-and-when-to-use-301-redirects-vs-canonical" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">how and when to use 301 redirects</a> as a good explanation of when to use a 301.   In summary, it's probably best to re-organize your content if you're using multiple re-directs.  This way, you can remove the multiple 301 re-directs and make it easier for the search engines (and your viewers) to understand where your content is located.<br />
<br />
Regards,<br />
Arnel C.</div>
